vacuate several thousand people during the civil war in sierra leone she is most noted for having been one of three state department officials to publicly resign in direct protest of the  invasion of iraq wright was also a passenger on the challenger  which along with the mavi marmara was part of the gaza flotilla contents  early life  us army  us state department  resignation  peace activism  gaza flotilla  september th attacks and the  commission report  writings  quotes  see also  references  external links early lifeedit wright grew up in bentonville arkansas in what she referred to as just a normal childhood she attended the university of arkansas where she was recruited in the us army wright earned a masters and law degrees while she worked for the us army her law degree comes from the university of arkansas and her masters degree in national security affairs is from the us naval war college us armyedit wright earned a masters degree in national security affairs from the us naval war college in newport rhode island and later participated in reconstruction efforts after us military actions in grenada and somalia wright was stationed at fort bragg north carolina from  to  one of her duties during that time was to draw up contingency plans for invading several countries one of which was iraq she would later express dismay over what she considered the dismissal of such carefully laid plans in the actual invasion of iraq in citation needed wright went on to serve  years in active duty in the us army and  years in the army reserves rising to the rank of colonel she was placed in the retired ready reserve meaning the president could call her back to active duty in a time of need us state departmentedit in  wright went to work for the foreign service within the us state department over the course of her state department career wright served as deputy chief of mission at the us embassies in afghanistan which she helped open following the  us invasion of afghanistan an assignment she volunteered for sierra leone an embassy which she helped close and then reopen again micronesia and mongolia and also served at us embassies in uzbekistan which she helped open kyrgyzstan grenada and nicaragua wrights eventual resignation was not the first time she had spoken out against policy in an interview wright said that she spoke out against united nations bombing tactics waged in somalia in the effort to kill rebel leader mohamed farrah aidid wright also says that she didnt agree with policy on multiple occasions but continued her state department work despite her own disagreements with the policy resignationedit wright submitted her resignation letter to then us secretary of state colin powell on march   the day before the onset of the  invasion of iraq her letter was published on the internet the following day in her resignation letter wright listed four reasons she could no longer work for the us government under the bush administration the decision to invade iraq without the blessing of the un security council the lack of effort in the israelipalestinian peace process the lack of policy in regard to north korea the curtailment of civil liberties within the united states wright was the third of three state department officials to retire from service in protest in the month prior to the invasion of iraq the other two being brady kiesling and john h brown wright says that she did not know the other two and had not read their resignation letters at the time she submitted her own peace activismedit protesting with code pink in  since her retirement from the state department wright has become a prominent figure in the movement opposed to the occupation of iraq she has attended many conferences and given numerous lectures on her political views and on her experiences before and after her resignation wright has worked with antiwar activist cindy sheehan on several occasions most notably by helping organize the camp casey demonstration outside george w bushs crawford texas ranch in august  and by accompanying the southern leg of the bring them home now bus tour she also volunteered at camp casey  the veterans for peace shelter for hurricane katrina victims in covington louisiana during the bus tour she marched with sheehan in  with the women say no to war campaign which was meant to deliver a petition with over  signatures of citizens against the war wright has willingly been arrested while taking part in antiwar demonstrations the first such arrest occurring in front of the white house on september   she has said in interviews that she does not remove the arrest bracelets attached to her wrists upon the processing of her arrest but rather collects them on october   wright interrupted a senate foreign relations committee hearing shouting at secretary of state condoleezza rice stop the war stop the killing wright was uneventfully escorted out of the hearing room wright served as one of five judges at the january  sessions of the international commission of inquiry on crimes against humanity committed by the bush administration she was also one of three recipients of the first annual truthout freedom and democracy awards wright was one of three witnesses called to testify at an article  hearing on behalf of us army lt ehren watada who on june   refused to deploy to iraq with his unit asserting that the war violates both the united states constitution and international law on april   wright was cited along with  other antinuclear activists for trespassing at the nevada test site during a nevada desert experience event protesting against the continued development of nuclear weapons by the united states that evening wright appeared on the oreilly factor to discuss the geneva conventions and how they applied to iran in its taking of  british hostages the discussion grew heated and wright stated that she had served  years in the military during the course of the exchange oreilly questioned wrights patriotism and when she pointed out she had served  years in the military and oreilly had never served at all her microphone was cut off on april   wright attended a hearing of a house foreign affairs subcommittee she was ejected from the hearing room after speaking out of turn in response to comments made by republican congressmember dana rohrabacher on september   wright was arrested and later convicted for disrupting a senate armed services committee hearing at which general david petraeus and ambassador to iraq ryan crocker were testifying wright took part in a september   protest march and diein on the steps of the united states capitol building organized by the answer coalition and iraq veterans against the war ivaw she was arrested for stepping over the wall after several ivaw and veterans for peace members were arrested on october   wright and code pink activist medea benjamin were denied entry to canada because their names appear on an fbi database called the national crime information center due to arrests related to their antiwar activism wright and benjamin were told that if they wish to enter canada in the future they will have to apply for residents permits in regards to the incident a canadian mp olivia chow was alarmed to learn that canadian border police are enforcinig rules that have been determined by the fbi and other usbased agencies in december  wright has recently expressed her dissatisfaction with the current us foreign policy toward palestine in  wright began work as a leading member of the steering committee for the gaza freedom march in august  she was among the signatories of an open letter to german chancellor angela merkel by the group veteran intelligence professionals for sanity in which they urged the chancellor to be suspicious of us intelligence regarding the alleged invasion of russia in eastern ukraine gaza flotillaedit main article gaza flotilla raid on june   wright was interviewed by democracy now she was on the challenger  and observed the isr